column102: Thomas Pollard (grandfather); Bettie (Turner) Pollard (grandmother)

column116: Birth date was 2/17/1918, per birth certificate and WWII draft registration. Mother's maiden name is Pollard; her (second) married name was Booker. He is buried in the same plot as his maternal grandparents, Thomas and Bettie Pollard.

Last name spelled variously Rodgers, Rogers. According to his sister Rebecca's death certificate, their mother's first name was Lucy — maybe short for Lutetia or Lucretia or some such? "Lewtrich" seems unlikely.

column54: This marker faces west at the end of a rectangular plot bordered by a low curb on three sides, composed of three rectangular slabs of concrete or soft stone, once secured by concrete. At the west side, there is no curb visible, but two rectangular posts seem to mark the entrance to the plot, on either side of the thin marker. A little further to the west is the marble socket base for a larger marble headstone (also for GW Smith) that now rests against the northern post. Inside the plot at the west side near the headstones and raised post are the fragments of at least two vessels (one ceramic with blue floral pattern, one white porcelain with relief design) and three conch shells.

A little further to the west is the marble socket base for a larger marble headstone (also for GW Smith) that now rests against the northern post. Inside the plot at the west side near the headstones and raised post are the fragments of at least two vessels (one ceramic with blue floral pattern, one white porcelain with relief design) and three conch shells.
